```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{automata,positioning}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[shorten >=1pt,node distance=2cm,on grid,auto]
    \node[state] (g3) {$g_3$};
    \node[state] (g4) [right=of g3] {$g_4$};

    \path[->]
        (g3) edge [loop left] node {$-2$} ()
             edge [bend right] node {$-2,0$} (g4)
        (g4) edge [loop right] node {$3$} ()
             edge [bend right] node {$1,3$} (g3);
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code will produce an automaton similar to the one shown in the image. The nodes are labeled as \( g_3 \) and \( g_4 \), and the transitions between them are labeled with the corresponding values. The arrows indicate the direction of the transitions, and the labels on the arrows represent the input values for each transition.

